Duke Ellington is good at jazz. He made music for a long time. He was good at making his group sound good. Ellington played the piano. He made music that was hard and new. He made music for his group to play. He made music so each player could play well. He made the group sound good together. Ellington knew how each player sounded. He knew how they sounded together. He made some of the best jazz music.

A book about music says Ellington used his voice like an instrument. He used it in a song called "Creole Love Call." He used his voice to make the music sound good. He did not use words. 

He also made the music sound good for his players. This song is slow. It has six parts.

*Part one:* A man and the woodwind players talk back and forth. The man sings first in a good way. Then he sings rougher.
*Part two:* A trumpet player plays softly. He plays the main song and some new notes.
*Part three:* A clarinet player plays high notes. The piano plays softly.
*Part four:* The whole group plays the first part. The brass and woodwind players talk back and forth.

*Part five:* This is the best part. The woodwind players sing first. They sing high notes. The brass and drum players stop and start.
*Part six:* This is like the first part. A man and the woodwind players talk back and forth. The man sings a rougher way.

The last part is short. It has a man singing and a trombone playing something strange.

Ellington used his voice to make music sound good. He did this in many songs. He made a song called "Hot and Bothered." He made the music sound good by using words and music.  He used a trumpet player named "Bubber" Miley. He used a singer named Baby Cox. They made a good sound together. He made another song called "It Don't Mean a Thing (If It Ain't Got That Swing)." He used a trombone player named Joe "Tricky Sam" Nanton. He played the main song on his trombone.

Exposition is hard. It can make a story bad.

Exposition is when a writer tells the reader things. It is not good to tell too much.

Brothers have a strong bond. This bond is strong and never goes away. Many things make up this bond: love, pride, jealousy, and meanness. Brothers know each other well. They know each other better than anyone else. They see themselves when they look at their brother. 

In hard times, the bond shows its true face. It can be good or bad. These feelings are strong and have big costs. To know these feelings, we must deal with the things that come with them. When you look at your brother, you see yourself. You see who you really are. Your actions show your real character.

In the story "The Scarlet Ibis," two brothers show this. They have many strong feelings. In a beautiful place, the brothers go on a trip that does not work.  Pride and sadness are strong in the end. Only one brother lives.

The story shows us the feelings of the brother named Doodle and his big brother. The story also shows us how the big brother sees the world. These things make the brother do things.

The big brother feels pride. From the time he and Doodle go outside together, the brother feels sad about Doodle. He wants a brother who can learn things like running, jumping, and climbing. He wants a brother to play with. But Doodle is sick. He can't do these things.

The brother is sad. He even thinks about hurting Doodle. But then Doodle smiles. The brother feels happy. This shows that he loves Doodle.

The brain is big and strong. It takes in new ideas. People used to think the brain was like a writing slate. Then they said it was like paper. Now they say it is like a computer. But the brain is more than just like these things. 

The brain takes in ideas from our five senses. We see, hear, touch, smell, and taste. These ideas go into the brain. The brain works hard to make sense of them. It looks for small parts and puts them together. It also uses what we already know to help us.

For example, if we see a black box, the brain uses what it knows about boxes to help us see it fast.

The brain is very good at picking out what is important. It helps us focus on what we need to see and hear. It blocks out the rest.

The brain keeps ideas in its memory. There are many kinds of memory. Some ideas stay for a short time. Others stay forever.

The brain uses many ways to keep ideas. It is still a big mystery how the brain works.

Aldous Huxley show bad things about new technology and money. He write a story called Brave New World. People in this story like to be with others. They like to be happy. The World Controller tell them what to think.

Marxist ideas help us see Huxley's worries. He talk about how money and things are the same. This show how Huxley think about money in his time.

Huxley use a Marxist idea called "false seeing." People do not see how money work. They want more things. This is bad. The World Controller make people want this. 

The World Controller is strong. The lower people are weak. The World Controller make the lower people happy by giving them things to buy.

People in Brave New World do not care about others. They do not love. They only care about looks and things. They are like robots. Huxley may say this is what happens when we have too much money and technology.
